{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Grb3NuZE2tpdoL1uy8AqiA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01QDtUKDvuTUkpDjKq3dMKMH","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"parameter":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"All direct and transitive dependencies are extracted from the manifest and included in the vulnerability check.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Transitive dependency extraction requires reading multiple manifest files (package.json → node_modules/*/package.json) or invoking a package manager. A Unit test with mocked file I/O would hide failures in how nested dependencies are discovered or traversed. Real failure boundary: code fails to walk the dependency tree correctly, missing some packages. This only surfaces when reading actual file structures (Integration) or invoking real tools (System).","test_description":"Create a temporary project directory with a package.json that has dependencies with their own nested dependencies (e.g., app depends on lodash, lodash depends on utility libs). Run the scanner and verify it extracts all transitive packages by comparing against a known-good list. Ensure the test uses real manifest files on disk, not mocked file operations.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The vulnerability database query returns results that match the exact version ranges in the manifest, not just the package name.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends entirely on the real vulnerability database API. A mocked API would always return whatever response the mock is configured to return, hiding real failures like malformed queries, incorrect version range formatting, API version mismatches, rate limiting, or authentication issues. Real failure boundary: scanner sends wrong query format to real API and gets incomplete/wrong results back. This cannot be caught with pure mocks.","test_description":"Call the real vulnerability database API (or use its staging environment) with actual package names and exact version ranges from a test manifest (e.g., 'lodash@^4.17.0'). Verify that the API returns correct CVEs for that version range, not just for any version of lodash. Confirm the query parameters are formed correctly and the response is parsed accurately.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The severity sorting places Critical above High above Medium above Low, with CVEs of the same severity sorted by CVSS score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure deterministic sorting logic on in-memory data. The input (CVE list) can be mocked or constructed from test data; the sorting algorithm has no external dependencies, no I/O, and no side effects. A mock API returning test CVEs is sufficient to verify the sort order. Real failure boundary: sorting comparator is broken (e.g., sorts descending instead of ascending, ignores CVSS for same severity). This is entirely testable at the function level.","test_description":"Create a list of CVE objects with mixed severities and CVSS scores (e.g., [Medium/5.0, Critical/9.0, High/7.5, Critical/8.5, Low/2.0]). Call the sort function and verify the output order is [Critical/9.0, Critical/8.5, High/7.5, Medium/5.0, Low/2.0]. Test edge cases: equal CVSS scores within same severity, all same severity, single CVE.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The manifest modification changes only the affected dependency's version, leaving all other entries unchanged.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This requires reading an actual manifest file, modifying it, and writing it back. Mocking file I/O operations would hide real failures: JSON/YAML parsing errors on malformed files, serialization losing formatting/comments, regex replacement being too greedy and affecting other fields, or file corruption. Real failure boundary: modified file is malformed, wrong fields changed, or formatting is lost. Must read/write actual files to catch these.","test_description":"Create a temporary manifest file (package.json with multiple dependencies: lodash@^4.0.0, express@^3.0.0, request@^2.0.0). Run the scanner to update only 'express' to ^4.0.0. Read the file back and verify: (1) express version changed, (2) lodash version unchanged, (3) request version unchanged, (4) file is valid JSON/YAML, (5) all fields are intact. Repeat with real-world manifest files from actual projects to catch edge cases.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The auto-generated pull request is created on the real repository with the correct single-dependency diff.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Creating a PR requires real Git operations (commit, push to remote) and/or calling the GitHub API. Mocking these would hide real failures: incorrect git config, wrong branch name, authentication failures, API rate limits, malformed commit messages, or incorrect diff generation. Real failure boundary: PR is created with wrong diff (e.g., multiple files changed), wrong branch, or auth fails at runtime. Cannot be caught without real subprocess/API calls.","test_description":"Set up a real test repository on GitHub (or use a local bare repo with remote simulation). Run the scanner to generate a dependency bump. Verify: (1) a new commit exists with exactly one file changed (the manifest), (2) the diff shows only the target dependency version changed, (3) a PR is opened with the correct title/description, (4) the PR diff contains only the single-dependency change. Test both happy path and